## Generate PDFs in a Next.js app

### Approach A: @react-pdf/renderer (Recommended for invoices, reports, structured docs)

#### 1. Install
```bash
npm install @react-pdf/renderer
```
- This library renders React components to a PDF binary. It runs on Node.js (server-side), NOT in the browser.
- Do NOT import it in Client Components — it will fail with a build error.

#### 2. Create a PDF template component
Create `lib/pdf/invoice-template.tsx`:
```tsx
import {
  Document,
  Page,
  Text,
  View,
  StyleSheet,
  Font,
} from '@react-pdf/renderer';

const styles = StyleSheet.create({
  page: {
    fontFamily: 'Helvetica',
    fontSize: 12,
    padding: 40,
    backgroundColor: '#ffffff',
  },
  header: {
    fontSize: 24,
    fontWeight: 'bold',
    marginBottom: 20,
  },
  row: {
    flexDirection: 'row',
    justifyContent: 'space-between',
    marginBottom: 8,
  },
  label: { color: '#666666' },
  value: { fontWeight: 'bold' },
  divider: {
    borderBottomWidth: 1,
    borderColor: '#eeeeee',
    marginVertical: 12,
  },
  total: {
    fontSize: 16,
    fontWeight: 'bold',
    textAlign: 'right',
    marginTop: 16,
  },
});

interface InvoiceProps {
  invoiceNumber: string;
  customerName: string;
  items: { description: string; quantity: number; unitPrice: number }[];
  issuedAt: string;
}

export function InvoiceDocument({ invoiceNumber, customerName, items, issuedAt }: InvoiceProps) {
  const total = items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.quantity * item.unitPrice, 0);

  return (
    <Document>
      <Page size="A4" style={styles.page}>
        <Text style={styles.header}>INVOICE</Text>
        <View style={styles.row}>
          <Text style={styles.label}>Invoice #</Text>
          <Text style={styles.value}>{invoiceNumber}</Text>
        </View>
        <View style={styles.row}>
          <Text style={styles.label}>Customer</Text>
          <Text style={styles.value}>{customerName}</Text>
        </View>
        <View style={styles.row}>
          <Text style={styles.label}>Date</Text>
          <Text style={styles.value}>{issuedAt}</Text>
        </View>
        <View style={styles.divider} />
        {items.map((item, i) => (
          <View key={i} style={styles.row}>
            <Text>{item.description} × {item.quantity}</Text>
            <Text>${(item.quantity * item.unitPrice).toFixed(2)}</Text>
          </View>
        ))}
        <View style={styles.divider} />
        <Text style={styles.total}>Total: ${total.toFixed(2)}</Text>
      </Page>
    </Document>
  );
}
```

#### 3. Create a download API route
Create `app/api/invoices/[id]/pdf/route.ts`:
```ts
import { renderToBuffer } from '@react-pdf/renderer';
import { InvoiceDocument } from '@/lib/pdf/invoice-template';
import { db } from '@/db';

export async function GET(
  _req: Request,
  { params }: { params: { id: string } }
) {
  const invoice = await db.query.invoices.findFirst({
    where: (inv, { eq }) => eq(inv.id, params.id),
    with: { items: true, customer: true },
  });

  if (!invoice) {
    return new Response('Not found', { status: 404 });
  }

  const buffer = await renderToBuffer(
    <InvoiceDocument
      invoiceNumber={invoice.number}
      customerName={invoice.customer.name}
      items={invoice.items}
      issuedAt={invoice.issuedAt.toLocaleDateString()}
    />
  );

  return new Response(buffer, {
    headers: {
      'Content-Type': 'application/pdf',
      'Content-Disposition': `attachment; filename="invoice-${invoice.number}.pdf"`,
      'Content-Length': buffer.byteLength.toString(),
    },
  });
}
```

#### 4. Trigger download from the UI
```tsx
// In a Server Component or Client Component
<a
  href={`/api/invoices/${invoiceId}/pdf`}
  download={`invoice-${invoiceNumber}.pdf`}
  className="btn"
>
  Download PDF
</a>
```
Using a plain `<a>` tag with `href` pointing to the API route is the simplest approach — no client-side JS needed.

---

### Approach B: Puppeteer (For HTML-to-PDF with exact browser rendering)

#### 1. Install
```bash
npm install puppeteer
```
Puppeteer downloads Chromium (~170MB). For Vercel, use `puppeteer-core` + `@sparticuz/chromium` to stay within the 50MB function limit.

For Vercel/serverless:
```bash
npm install puppeteer-core @sparticuz/chromium-min
```

#### 2. Create a PDF generator utility
Create `lib/pdf/generate.ts`:
```ts
import puppeteer from 'puppeteer';

export async function generatePdfFromUrl(url: string): Promise<Buffer> {
  const browser = await puppeteer.launch({
    headless: true,
    args: ['--no-sandbox', '--disable-setuid-sandbox'],
  });
  const page = await browser.newPage();
  await page.goto(url, { waitUntil: 'networkidle0' });
  const pdf = await page.pdf({
    format: 'A4',
    printBackground: true,
    margin: { top: '40px', bottom: '40px', left: '40px', right: '40px' },
  });
  await browser.close();
  return Buffer.from(pdf);
}

export async function generatePdfFromHtml(html: string): Promise<Buffer> {
  const browser = await puppeteer.launch({
    headless: true,
    args: ['--no-sandbox', '--disable-setuid-sandbox'],
  });
  const page = await browser.newPage();
  await page.setContent(html, { waitUntil: 'networkidle0' });
  const pdf = await page.pdf({ format: 'A4', printBackground: true });
  await browser.close();
  return Buffer.from(pdf);
}
```

For Vercel (serverless):
```ts
import chromium from '@sparticuz/chromium-min';
import puppeteer from 'puppeteer-core';

export async function generatePdfServerless(html: string): Promise<Buffer> {
  const browser = await puppeteer.launch({
    args: chromium.args,
    defaultViewport: chromium.defaultViewport,
    executablePath: await chromium.executablePath(
      'https://github.com/Sparticuz/chromium/releases/download/v123.0.1/chromium-v123.0.1-pack.tar'
    ),
    headless: chromium.headless,
  });
  const page = await browser.newPage();
  await page.setContent(html, { waitUntil: 'networkidle0' });
  const pdf = await page.pdf({ format: 'A4', printBackground: true });
  await browser.close();
  return Buffer.from(pdf);
}
```

#### 3. Add max duration for serverless functions
If deploying on Vercel, Puppeteer can be slow — increase the function timeout:
```ts
// At the top of your route.ts
export const maxDuration = 30; // seconds
```

---

### Choosing between the two approaches
| Factor | @react-pdf/renderer | Puppeteer |
|---|---|---|  
| Bundle size | ~5MB | ~170MB (full) / use chromium-min for serverless |
| Speed | Fast (< 100ms) | Slow (2-10s, browser startup) |
| Layout control | JSX-based PDF primitives | Exact CSS rendering |
| Best for | Invoices, receipts, reports | Existing HTML pages, complex CSS layouts |
| Vercel/Edge | Yes (Node.js runtime) | Needs extra setup (`@sparticuz/chromium`) |

### Common Errors & Fixes
- **`Error: Text strings must be rendered inside a <Text> component`** — In @react-pdf/renderer, ALL text must be inside `<Text>`. No raw strings in `<View>` children.
- **`Module not found: canvas`** — @react-pdf/renderer's optional canvas dependency missing on some platforms. It's not required — ignore this warning or add `"canvas": false` to your webpack `externals`.
- **Puppeteer timeout on Vercel** — Default 10s function timeout is too short. Set `export const maxDuration = 30` in the route file.
- **Puppeteer bundle too large** — Do not use `puppeteer` on Vercel; switch to `puppeteer-core` + `@sparticuz/chromium-min`.
- **PDF renders without styles** — Puppeteer screenshot vs PDF: CSS `@media print` rules apply to PDFs. Add `printBackground: true` to `page.pdf()` options.
- **`Cannot use JSX in .ts files`** — Rename `invoice-template.ts` to `invoice-template.tsx` — @react-pdf/renderer uses JSX.
- **Font not loading in @react-pdf** — Register custom fonts with `Font.register()` before using them in `StyleSheet`. Web fonts from URLs work but add latency; prefer bundled font files.
- **`renderToBuffer is not a function`** — You imported from `@react-pdf/renderer/node` or the wrong sub-export. The correct import is `import { renderToBuffer } from '@react-pdf/renderer'`.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT use @react-pdf/renderer in Client Components — it requires Node.js APIs and will fail at build time.
- Do NOT use standard CSS class names in @react-pdf/renderer — it uses its own `StyleSheet.create()` with a subset of Flexbox, not full CSS.
- Do NOT use Puppeteer on Vercel Serverless Functions without `@sparticuz/chromium-min` — the full Chromium binary exceeds the 50MB limit.
- Do NOT leave Puppeteer browser instances open — always `await browser.close()` in a `finally` block to prevent memory leaks.
- Do NOT generate PDFs synchronously on every page request without caching — generate on demand and store the result in object storage (S3/R2) for repeat downloads.
- Do NOT pass raw user input directly into HTML rendered by Puppeteer — sanitize first to prevent XSS in the PDF.
